<br>
This was a special situation. The apprentice of the Dismal Rage that was killed, was an unusually skilled young Magician. Also an exceptionally independent, young woman. A young woman who was, from time to time, Daon's lover. Not &quot;Lover&quot; in the emotional sense. No &quot;Love&quot; sang by Bards in taverns, to keep happy couples warm at night. &quot;Lovers&quot; in a more physical sense. Despite his relentless studies in dark secrets. Despite his constant exercise to keep up his health and strength, Daon was still a man like many men. He had his own needs, as did the young woman who studied the art of Magicians. He had been attracted to her inner strength. Her intelligence. That made Daon look away from his studies to notice her exceptional beauty. <br>
Now she was dead. Daon felt a strange sense of loss. An emptiness that grew with the pain he felt from another lifetime. A &quot;memory&quot; of a woman he could &quot;feel&quot; but not remember. He knew he never shared his past life with this...mystery woman. Yet a pain haunted Daon at odd times when he was alone. Now the pain mingled with the loss of the apprentice he respected and shared his bed with.<br>
Daon slowly walked out of the tunnels and into the sunlight. Looking.<br>
<br>
Elsewhere, in the Western Commonlands. A young Shadowknight, recently achieving his Ninth Season, practiced his new skills in Necromantic Arts with a hunger. He was determined to be the best he could be in the Dismal Rage. He was a &quot;Chosen One&quot;. Nearly immortal. Death only made him shed his old form like a snake skin, to be reborn again. The &quot;unkillable&quot; enemy. Death could only hold &quot;Chosen Ones&quot; if their will to live stopped. Other wise they would live forever. And forever, was what the Shadowknight looked forward to. Dark dreams and dark glory. Women to want and treasure to take.<br>
As the Shadowknight finished his practice, becoming as skilled as he could be for his Season, he walked along the deep green of the Western Commonlands. He enjoyed the feel of the cool wind that picked up. Slightly shivering when the wind hit the sweat on his body. His armor was a tombstone grey, with engravings of torture and masochism. An inheritance he enjoyed wearing for it's shocking imagery. He kept his head and his face clean shaven. A black eye patch covered his right eye. A memento of earlier battles. Life of cruelty, sadism, rape and ruin suited the young Shadowknight of the Dismal Rage.<br>
<br>
 He noticed the two Druids that guarded the ruins in the middle of the Western Commonlands, were not there. Perhaps they had been murdered again. They were always making enemies in a world where they had enough enemies. He wandered by the merchant, looking her up and down in predatory fashion. She was a young but experienced merchant. Capable of defending her self. Too well, for the Shadowknight. He didn't like the ones with enough inner strength to fight back. Perhaps in time though.<br>
Acting &quot;innocent&quot; and walking by the young merchant at the ruins, the Shadowknight almost tripped over a piece of old bone sticking out of the ground. Recently unearthed by an apparent battle where the Shadowknight stood. &quot;No doubt, those stupid Druids were killed by some Wizard.&quot; the Shadowknight muttered to himself, looking at the damage covering the surrounding area, as he bent down to inspect the exposed bones.<br>
<br>
Daon stood still. Only slightly turning his head side to side as he watched adventurers run around the Eastern Commonlands. Behind him to his right, stood an unholy abomination of black magic and bones. A skeleton possessed by a spirit of death. Some Necromancers and Shadowknights summoned the ghost of the once living. Daon had learned a secret form one of his favorite teachers in the Dismal Rage. <br>
<br>
There were spirits of death that could answer the call. Ghost were the once living. Ghost were what many people called &quot;spirits&quot;. These ghost, were what many who practiced the Death Arts summoned to animate their skeleton servants. Spirits, true spirits, had never lived at all. Entities that could be friendly...or monsters. Spirits from a realm of death. A place the &quot;once living&quot; passed by, on the way to their god's domain. Spirits who dwelled in a place some called the &quot;land of the dead&quot;. Not demons, creatures of darker power, but spirits who hated the living. Jealous of the living, but incredibly loyal to whoever summoned them into the physical world. Daon's servants were always quite single minded, in their hatred of the living. No one could hear them chant and whisper, but Daon could, in his mind. Soon, he would have to gain the magic to allow his skeleton servant to speak in the material world. It would be amusing to listen to physically.<br>
<br>
Daon blinked. He had been lost in thought. Thinking of the spirits who served him from the land of the dead. He almost didn't see the warrior passing by in the distance. The Warrior, Daon knew was the one who killed his &quot;lover&quot;.<br>
As Daon looked at the Steel Warrior, the undead servant hissed and clawed at the air. Sensing his master's thoughts. Looking around briefly to make certain no wandering guards of Freeport would interfere, Daon said in a low and cultured voice, &quot;Servant...kill the Steel Warrior.&quot;<br>
<br>
The old bones should not have been there. The Shadowknight was confused. The land claimed all things in time. Bodies would disappear, belongings dropped would &quot;fade away&quot;. The magic that flowed through all things made it so. In a sense, all things came from the earth and all things would be &quot;reclaimed&quot;. The Shadowknight unearthed the remaining bones. He found enough to use for summoning a skeleton pet of his own. He could tell the bones came from one source. A large, powerful, humanoid creature. Holding the large bones in his hands, the Shadowknight could sense power in them. Magic he did not recognize, but strong enough to keep the bones intact despite the passing of time. Smiling to himself, the Shadowknight quickly placed the bones in his traveling bag and ran towards home in Freeport.<br>
<br>
Daon took his time walking back towards Freeport, but kept to the edge of the East Commonlands. Away from guard's eyes. Behind him, the skeletal servant dragged a barely alive body of the Steel Warrior by the hair. Daon ordered the undead servant to stop attacking before the Warrior died. Daon wanted him alive.<br>
<br>
To be continued...<br>
