<br>
&quot;I have brought the one you saw, Prophet of Rage.&quot; he began. His voice low and respectful. Echoing in the secret chamber. &quot;He is now tied to an examination table in a private chamber. Awaiting his punishment.&quot; The beautiful prophet, floating in the air above Daon, nodded her head. As she spoke, her voice seemed to come from the four corners of the room, rather from her mouth. &quot;I sensed it when you found him &quot;Daon, Once Daon Wolf&quot;. Soon to be Daon Wolf again.&quot; <br>
<br>
The Prophet of Rage knew of the Necromancer's past existence. It was their &quot;secret&quot; together. There was no true &quot;trust&quot; in the world of those who served dark gods. Yet Daon felt no alarm when she first addressed him as &quot;Daon, Once Daon Wolf&quot;. He did not know why he felt safe with her knowledge of him. Anyone could use knowledge to gain power over another somehow, someway. The Necromancer, strangely, was not alarmed when she revealed her knowledge of him. &quot;I trust you will punish him appropriately.&quot; she said. Her eyes looking at the hood that covered Daon's head. Daon felt she could see him through the hood. He never felt the need to remove it in her presence out of courtesy. She could see into his soul. There was nothing to hide from her. <br>
<br>
 Elsewhere, in the underground base of the Dismal Rage, the Shadowknight emptied the bones out of his bag with a loud rattle. He could feel the magic. Almost see it. Glowing. If he was successful, he would have a powerful skeletal pet to serve him. He believed the pet would last forever. Not dissipating when nearing towns or new lands. The magic the Conclave Empire established in various areas to &quot;guard&quot; from some unknown attack. Areas, the Shadowknight assumed, where the old empire had planned to set up kingdoms. The magic near cities and even unsettled lands, repelled most pets and sometimes monsters. No one knew how this magic worked or the exact reason &quot;why&quot; it was there. It was believed, therefore, that the now dead empire made it so. But the magic could have been even older for all anyone knew.<br>
If these bones were as strong as the Shadowknight thought, his pet would resist the magic and possibly grow ever stronger. The Shadowknight smiled at this idea. He did not truly know if this would work. But the dreams of true arrogance did not allow for the possibility of being wrong. The Shadow knight never believed he could be wrong. He began casting his spell when he suddenly stopped. He put his thumb to his chin as he thought. Still wearing his armor and gauntlets, his metal covered thumb caressed the cleft in his chin as he pondered. &quot;If I make it here...some of the elders may see it and try to claim it's power for their own.&quot; he said softly to himself. Without thinking twice, the Shadowknight quickly slid the bones off the table and into the travelling bag. Tieing the bag closed, he hefted the bag over his shoulder and quickly ran out of the underground base of the Dismal Rage.<br>
<br>
Daon entered the private chamber where he held the Steel Warrior. Daon, slowly walked around the table where the Warrior was tied on his back. Daon watched him. The warrior had awaken. Struggling with the leather bonds that kept his arms and legs still. A leather strap holding his head in place. Daon had tended to his wounds. No need to let him die yet. The Warrior's armor had been removed and set aside within view of the Warrior. The weapons nearby, also in view. Just out of reach. This was intended for a psychological effect. The armor was the Warrior's protection. Having it arranged and placed within view reminded the Warrior of his vulnerability. The weapons were part of his strength. The weapons reminded the Warrior of his helplessness.<br>
 Daon slowly continued to walk around the table, keeping his head turned towards the Warrior. Even though none of Daon's features could be seen in the shadows of Daon's hood, it told the Warrior that Daon was always watching him. Watching his struggle without saying a word. <br>
<br>
Calmly walking in front of the Warrior, then around behind the Warrior's head, where the Warrior could not see him. Then down along the side, close to the struggling hands that tried to reach and grab Daon. Just out of reach. Only when the Warrior tired himself out, did Daon stop at the left side of the table. He stood still. Red, gloved hands clasped together in front of him, looking down at the Warrior. The only light was two candles near the Warrior's equipment. The armor at the foot of the table with one candle. The weapons at the right of the Warrior with the other candle. Everything else was faint darkness and total blackness. The blood red robes of the Necromancer stood out like a reminder that the Warrior was not alone. Daon had not spoken a single word.<br>
<br>
The Shadowknight found an abandoned hut in the East Commonlands. Sitting down for a moment to regain his strength. The Shadowknight felt excitement at the prospect of a large undead servant, fighting at his command. Getting back to his feet. The Shadowknight began to cast his spell of forming the bones into a complete skeleton. Summoning one of the dead to animate the bones and serve his will. The green magic spread outward form his armored body. He could feel the power within the large, old bones reacting to his spell. It was working. The sound of bone clicking on bone filled the abandoned hut. Green light filled the hut as a large, almost giant skeleton began to form.<br>
<br>
&quot;You... are the Warrior, who killed a rather...unique Magician a few days ago.&quot; Daon said. His voice calm. He took his time speaking. The Warrior himself had not said a word. Determined not to give in to the weakness of fear. Many people, even if not begging, would have said something by now. At least demanding what the Necromancer wanted from them. The Steel Warrior was stronger than that. No one became a Warrior by being soft.<br>
&quot;You mean the slut.&quot; the Warrior taunted. His eyes cold and unafraid. &quot;Slut...&quot; Daon echoed. No emotional reaction, like the Warrior wanted. Rather, the Necromancer seemed to examine the word by speaking it. &quot;When a man calls a woman a &quot;slut&quot;...he is actually, on some level, whether aware of it or not, jealous that HE is not the one the woman is &quot;playing&quot; with. All men believe, somewhere deep inside, that all &quot;attractive&quot; women should be HIS.&quot; The Necromancer began to slowly walk around the captured Warrior again. Still speaking slowly. He paced when he was in deep thought. &quot;I know this, because despite the pursuit of power that occupies my time, I am also a MAN. Unlike most men, I am not insecure, and can admit these &quot;things&quot; freely.&quot;<br>
The Warrior began to laugh. &quot;You are an idiot! You have no idea what you are talking about! Let me off this table and I'll teach you how a man fights! No words! No pets! No coward tactics! You are pathetic!&quot; <br>
The Necromancer, did not stop his slow walk around the table. He did not react to the Warrior's words, merely letting the Warrior speak his mind. It would give the Warrior confidence, hearing himself. Daon wanted him to feel that. All the more painful then, when the Necromancer would begin the Warrior's &quot;education.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Odd isn't it?&quot; said Daon. &quot;You are the hero. You oppose all the gods of darkness, fighting all evil you come across. I...am a monster. A Necromancer in service to Innoruuk and the Dismal Rage. Yet, &quot;I&quot; the monster, am more honest than the hero.&quot; The Warrior laughed. &quot;Your an idiot!&quot; the Warrior said. Daon took his time walking away into the darkest corner of the room. The corner was within view of the Warrior. The Necromancer made sure of this. The Warrior could no longer see Daon. Only hear the sounds of glass clicking against something. The Necromancer, just as slowly, reappeared walking towards the Warrior with a glass vial in his right hand.<br>
&quot;Time for your first lesson.&quot; Daon said. He felt the time was right. &quot;You only thing you can teach me is how to be a coward and talk too much!&quot; The Warrior retorted.<br>
<br>
&quot;Your first lesson...&quot; Daon calmly spoke, &quot;is that acid should be weakened by adding equal parts water to it. If acid burns through the victim, then the torture will end too quickly by the threat of death.&quot; Daon stood at the top of the table, over the warrior's head. &quot;Second lesson..&quot; The Necromancer slowly said, &quot;Courage, for many people, can be situational. We will see, if yours holds up over pain.&quot; Daon carefully poured the acid onto the Warrior's eyes. The struggling Warrior grunted as he resisted the pain. Then began to howl and scream as the acid ate through the eyelids and into the eyes.<br>
<br>
The large skeleton formed in a kneeling position. Unusual for the formation of a pet. Most undead servants formed standing, ready for action. The Shadowknight noticed this but did not care. His servant had formed. The spell successful. Now he only needed to test the power of his new pet. &quot;Stand up!&quot; the Shadowknight ordered, breathing heavily, excited by his success. The large skeleton arched it's back with the front of the skull looking up at the ceiling and roared in a powerful, looming voice. It seemed to roar forever. The sound hurting the ears of the Shadowknight, causing him to cover them with his armored hands. Suddenly, the large skeleton stopped with a surprising quickness. It's lower jaw bone snapping shut with a loud click of teeth over teeth. At the same time, the skull quickly turned it's head towards the Shadowknight. It's left arm shoot out like a flash of light. It's bony digits smashing through the Shadowknight's teeth and into his mouth, clamping down on the tongue. Bending at the wrist bones, the &quot;palm&quot; of the skeleton's hand supported the Shadowknight's head, as it lifted him up. Standing up to it's full height. Towering over anyone of human size, the large skeleton held the struggling Shadowknight up at arm's length. Blood poured out of the captured Shadowknight's mouth, over the skeleton's fingers and dripped to the floor.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh no.&quot; The large skeleton's voice boomed, even though it spoke calmly in a course whisper. &quot;Oh no, I don't think you will be giving orders to me.&quot; The large skeleton said, tilting it's head to the side, looking at the Shadowknight. It's tone mocking. The fingers of the skeleton's right hand, unbuckled and dropped the Shadowknight's weapons. The loud clang of the weapons hitting the floor, mingled with the muffled growls of pain by the Shadowknight. &quot;You won't be needing those.&quot; the large skeleton stated casually. &quot;Will you?&quot; The undead creature quickly brought the Shadowknight close to his &quot;face&quot;. The Shadowknight's enraged eyes close to the empty sockets of the large skeleton. The undead abomination seemed to be &quot;sniffing&quot; the blood pouring from the mouth. If a skeleton with no lips could smile, the Shadowknight could have sworn the undead creature began to grin. &quot;Will you, &quot;Chosen One&quot;!<br>
<br>
To be continued...<br>
