<br>
The Shadowknight grabed at the large skeleton's skull with both hands. Red, firey magic flashed out of the Shadowknight as his Harmtouch made the skeleton roar with pain. Small parts of the skull exploded outward from the unholy magic. The Shadowknight fell painfully to the floor as the skeleton released him and staggered back, clutching at it's damaged skull. The Shadowknight scampered towards his weapons, ignoring the throbbing pain of his mouth. He grabbed the handle of his longsword and pulled. The sound of steel, sliding along the inside of the scabbard as he pulled the weapon out, filled the hut. The Shadowknight quickly turned to face the undead creature but no one was there. The Shadowknight charged towards the doorway to hunt the creature down, then felt the impact of a large skeletal fist colliding with his face. The Shadowknight was thrown off his feet and onto his back. His body made a loud 'thud' as it hit the floor. His weapon was thrown out of his hand by the impact, making a loud racket as the sword fell to the side. <br>
In the doorway of the hut, the large skeleton peeked into the room. Upside down. It was easy for the creature, even with it's size, to slip out the door and leap onto the roof. Ready to attack from above. There was no bulk of muscle on it's bones to trap it in the doorway. The creature was more silent and nimble than any undead should be.<br>
&quot;We're not finished playing yet.&quot; the large skeleton said as it looked, upside down, at the barely conscience Shadowknight.<br>
<br>
When, and only when, the Steel Warrior stopped screaming from pain, did Daon cast another spell. An unusual comfort overcame the Warrior, as small amounts of the torture done to him healed. Just enough to for his eyes to reform. Just enough for him to see and to pay attention to something besides the pain. The Necromancer made sure the Warrior could see him well enough, as he slowly walked past the warrior's feet. The red robed and hooded magic user, stopped besides the Warrior's armor. Making certain the armor his captive used, was in his line of sight. All the more to remind the fighter of his vulnerability. Daon felt weak from using some of his own lifeforce to heal the Warrior, but made certain he did not show it.<br>
&quot;Lesson three. If too much pain is a constant sensation, the victim's body has a chance to adapt, one way or another. I have no intention of letting you get used to pain. Besides...I DO want you to see what I am doing to you.&quot; Daon took his time, walking back into the shadows of the corner, where he kept the equipment. The Warrior could not see the Necromancer in the darkest part of the room, only hear the sounds of metal tools being gathered. The Steel Warrior tried to pull his arm off the table that was pinned by the dagger, but could not find the strength. If only he could see the damn Necromancer and what he was doing.<br>
<br>
Daon pushed a cart with various blades arranged on it, up to the side of the Warrior. Daon had no intention of using the blades on his captive. He had no taste for physical torture beyond what he had already done. Daon felt &quot;above&quot; pure physical torture. But the sharp blades would have a good psychological effect, being within sight. When Daon thought of what he had planned for the Warrior, he paused for a moment and wondered if it would be more merciful to &quot;just&quot; torture him in the &quot;usual&quot; way. The idea Daon came up with while talking to the Warrior, might seem to some people, to be worse.<br>
&quot;We are not finished yet...&quot; The Necromancer said, as he brought out a large box filled with various spiders.<br>
