There is no final death for &quot;Chosen Ones&quot;. Die, only to be reborn again, like a snake shedding a skin. Only their will to live, determined if they could truly die.<br>
Something was wrong.<br>
The eyes of the first Shadowknight were wide open. Barely alive, head shaking side to side in denial and panic. Seeing the inside of the hut flash by, as his head turned one way. Seeing the gore covered, large skull in front of him, screaming in mockery of the Shadowknight's screams, as he turned his head the other way. Hands trembling in vain to grab and fight the undead creature, as it slowly ate him alive. Every time the creature bit him, the Shadowknight lost the will to live. The large skeleton was &quot;eating&quot; his will to live. The woman who came to rescue the male Shadowknight, was already dead. Truly dead. The man knew it. Somewhere in the chaos of his pain, fear and thoughts, he knew she was truly dead. Not reborn. Not coming back with reinforcements. The undead monster ate her quickly, almost mercifully. The undead creature, took it's time with the male Shadowknight.<br>
<br>
The Steel Warrior turned his head to the side in reflex, as he saw the vial of acid over his head. No pain came. No searing, burning agony. The Warrior looked back towards the Necromancer and saw him reaching with his other hand towards the large box sitting on the Warrior's crotch.<br>
&quot;Try not to do... what is expected of you.&quot; Daon said as he removed the lid of the box and overturned it onto the Warrior's stomach. A dozen large and small spiders quickly tumbled and scampered out. A few looked as if they were trying to eat each other. Most started to crawl.<br>
 Over the Warrior's stomach. Over his his arms. Even down to his legs. One spider, seemed interested in the dagger still imbedded in the Warrior's arm, pinning him to the table. A dozen spiders crawling, searching the Warrior's body. One large, black spider rushed up the Warrior's chest and towards his face. The Warrior could almost see his face reflected in the multiple eyes of the black spider, as it stopped at his chin.<br>
<br>
Daon slowly walked towards the center of the room. A chain hung from the ceiling, attached to a round trap door. The door covered a hole that led to the surface. An air vent that led to a spot just outside the city. Magic kept the smaller vermin of the area from messing with the air shaft. Magic also kept the air shaft clean. Daon pulled on the chain, opening the trap door in the ceiling. Light came down as if a bright torch illuminated the tunnel. A cool breeze came through, followed by light rain. Daon stood underneath the air shaft. Tilting his head back, letting his hood fall. His long, light blond hair reached down past his shoulders. His face, young and clean shaven, was lightly pelted by the rain drops. Daon just stood there, feeling the rain on his face.<br>
&quot;There are different kinds of evil, Steel Warrior...&quot; Daon said. His voice lower and more thoughtful, than a young man of his age should have been. &quot;There is what I like to call &quot;Noble Evil&quot; or &quot;Divine Evil&quot;. ...Those of use who draw a line and call it honor.&quot; Daon's eyes were closed. His face and hair now wet with the rain. He continued talking, not knowing if the Warrior was paying attention. Not caring.<br>
 &quot;It is what makes us different, from &quot;other&quot; evil that has no honor, no code. Little more than beasts on two legs.&quot; The Warrior did not move as he looked at the large, black spider. The spider, looking at him.<br>
Spiders had already bitten him. He could feel his skin swelling with irritation at the small fangs. At the spider venom. He controlled his pain. The Steel Warrior would not die screaming at spiders. He would not allow himself to die that way.<br>
<br>
&quot;...Some people think, that because &quot;Noble Evil&quot; shows self-control, even respect, in certain situations, that we could never be as vicious as the &quot;other&quot; evils. ...They have no idea.&quot; The Warrior's body twitched in pain involuntarily. Some spiders reacted in fear and moved away. Some became more violent and bit again. The black spider at the Warrior's chin, tapped his lower lip with one of it's long, hairy legs. The Warrior tried to control his breathing. To calm down his body. &quot;The cold truth is... that ALL beings, Good and Evil have a...horrible...&quot;monster&quot; inside. This &quot;monster&quot;, is the cruelty, anger, and potential for madness, we all have within.&quot; Daon still stood under the air vent, in the rain. Talking, thinking more to himself, than to his prisoner. &quot;With no control, the &quot;monster&quot; can go beyond all preconceptions of evil and past insanity. I tap into my &quot;monster&quot; in order to BE a monster. I use &quot;it&quot; to gain power. To do what is necessary to survive.&quot; Daon opened his eyes. Watching for a moment, the rain fall towards him like a hundred falling stars. &quot;You would not want to believe the things I have seen. Most of it memories from a past...time. Death, quiet oblivion, with no gods to pull our destines, would be a sweet release. Sometimes I think that.&quot; Daon, slightly covering his eyes with his right hand to keep water out, watched the rain fall from above. &quot;...Wash away the memories.&quot;<br>
<br>
The door to the abandoned hut opened. Flies gathered around the building, looking for the source of the grotesque smell from within. A large skeleton, bent over to allow itself room to exit, stepped out of the hut. Standing up to it's full height, it stretched as if it felt cramped from being in so small a space for it's large form. Tattered sheets of human skin, sewn together with strips of sinew and bone, covered it's skull like an executioner's hood. There were two holes for the eyes on the hood of flesh. One large hole for the mouth. Blue magic flowed from the large skeleton's hands. Surrounding the creature with power. With the Spirit of the Wolf. &quot;I feel...like a new Ogre!&quot; The large skeleton laughed and ran with magic speed. Disappearing into the forest of the East Commonlands.<br>
<br>
Daon stood over the captive Steel Warrior. &quot;You are lucky I am your torturer. Some people, thinking they are more terrifying or impressive by being more debased, would have defiled you. While using magic to force you to defile someone you cared for. Then possibly eating you alive. Or even during.&quot;  Daon put his hood back on, covering his wet features. The Warrior, feeling physically and even emotionally weaker, still refused to give in. &quot;Oh, I am so &quot;honored&quot; you are my local madman!&quot; <br>
Daon picked up the large, black spider on the Warrior's chin and held it over the Warrior's face. Close to his face. Two orcs with green skin, appeared out of the dark of the other side of the room. One holding the Warrior's head still. The other forcing open the Warrior's mouth. Had they been there the whole time? The Warrior could not think clearly enough to answer his own inner question. Daon, the Necromancer in red, held the large spider close to the Warrior's mouth. &quot;Think before you speak.&quot; was all Daon said. Then placed the spider in the Steel Warrior's mouth.<br>
