rior's arm with a dagger. The spiders crawling on the Warrior's body either crawled away, frightened by the shaking or became agitated and bit more. The Necromancer felt more sympathy for the frightened spider, than he ever could for the Steel Warrior. &quot;You could continue to struggle...hoping you will find the strength to force open your mouth and spit out the spider...or you could...swallow.&quot; <br>
<br>
Daon stood there calmly, quietly. His hands once more together as if he were in meditation. Looking straight ahead, his features still covered by the hood of his red robe. Making him look like some distant, untouchable, red ghost. Part of this was Daon's nature. To seem &quot;aloof&quot;. Part of this was to make the Steel Warrior feel as if he could not &quot;touch&quot; Daon. Untouchable, unbeatable. As if nothing the Warrior could do would make a difference. Everything the Necromancer did, was a subtle psychological attack.<br>
Daon waited a few more patient moments, then gestured to the orc guards to release the Warrior's head and jaw. The Steel Warrior spit out the crumpled looking and angry arachnid. It scuttled away into the shadows. The Warrior was too busy coughing and gagging to say anything. Daon gestured to the orc guards and then to the door. &quot;Leave him for now. Let us give him a moment alone to think. ...The spiders will keep him company.&quot; The orcs opened the door and walked out. Daon snuffed out the two candles in the room, then slowly walked out the doorway, surrounded by the light from the hall. The Necromancer turned around to look at the Warrior covered in spiders, then closed the door leaving him alone in the dark.<br>
<br>
Daon paused at the door of the Prophet's room, awaiting permission to enter. The door opened by itself and Daon walked inside. The Prophet of Rage floated in the middle of the room. Daon stopped a few feet away and looked up at her. &quot;Have they been found?&quot; the Necromancer asked.<br>
 The Prophet nodded as she talked. &quot;They are being held in another room.&quot;<br>
&quot;Thank you.&quot; Daon replied. Satisfaction in his voice. &quot;Now all I need to do, is prepare the dead apprentice's body for the funeral and one of our &quot;guests&quot; as a sacrifice.&quot;<br>
&quot;There has been a change in your plans.&quot; came a snide voice from the side. A priest of Hate, a new arrival in the Dismal Rage, with more status than usual due to &quot;political connections&quot; within the Rage. He enjoyed &quot;pushing&quot; whoever he could with his political status. There were a dozen Clerics of Innoruuk who were more qualified for his position. But sometimes, politics ruled. &quot;The dead apprentice was not important enough for the unholy funeral. Her body was left to rot.&quot; The Priest sneered. &quot;The earth has reclaimed her.&quot; The Priest enjoyed this opportunity to &quot;push&quot; Daon.<br>
Daon did not flinch. Grateful he left his hood on, for the Priest may have seen the anger in Daon's eyes. The Necromancer was more emotional than he was in his previous life as a Shadowknight. He was learning that emotions, although leaving him vulnerable in some ways, was a good source of strength in other ways.  He closed his eyes and sighed. He had wanted to give his former lover a farewell worthy of her inner strength and beauty. Now, with her truly gone, Daon must find another way. &quot;Prophet of Rage...&quot; Daon said very slowly, his voice low and thoughtful. &quot;...what would be the price of your silence?&quot; The Prophet looked at Daon, her eyes meeting his under the hood. &quot;You will have to be creative.&quot; she said, &quot;I need no money.&quot; <br>
&quot;Entertainment?&quot; the Necromancer asked. The Prophet narrowed her eyes at Daon, wondering what he meant. Daon turned his head slightly enough to look at the sneering Priest.<br>
&quot;Whisper..&quot; was all Daon said. A sleek, black cat with golden eyes appeared on Daon's shoulders. Mewing like a kitten, as it peeked around Daon's hood and looked at his face. The Necromacer pointed his finger at the Priest. &quot;...eat his bowels.&quot; Daon said angrily. The cat leaped out at the shocked priest with supernatural quickness, slamming into his face with more force than the cat's body should have had. The Priest hit the floor, stunned. The cat easily landed on it's feet, then quickly darted at the barely conscious man. Ripping and tearing into the Priest's unarmored body with unusual ease. The Priest tried to struggle, but Daon placed his boot on the man's neck, holding him down and choking him. Daon tilted his head towards the face of the shaking and dying priest. &quot;You &quot;pushed&quot; me, Priest. You &quot;pushed&quot; me...and this is my way...of &quot;pushing&quot; back. <br>
<br>
Daon did not look back to see if the Prophet would interfere or attack him. Even though his back was exposed to her, Daon did not care. A mistake, perhaps but Daon's quiet hatred for the man who ruined his plans and sneered at him, would not let go.  The cat's growling seemed to echo from inside the Priest's body as it ate his bowels. The Priest stopped struggling as his eyes grew wide, then lifeless.<br>
&quot;What is that cat and how did you find it?&quot; the Prophet asked calmly, despite the gory spectacle in front of her. Daon's head tilted up, facing a wall. The floating Prophet was still behind him. Daon's blue eyes were cold and focused even though looking at nothing. &quot;There are some things..even you cannot see, Prophet.&quot; the Necromacer said. He slowly turned to look at the Prophet. &quot;Secrets Best, are Secrets Kept.&quot; he said slowly. The Prophet floated close to Daon and &quot;looked&quot; into his soul. She would find her answers by searching his memories.<br>
